          <h3>Choosing a Method</h3>

          <p>No single charting method is best for every woman. The choice depends on a woman's health goals, cycle characteristics, comfort with different observation techniques, and whether she plans to work with an RRM physician. Women with PCOS or irregular cycles may benefit from the objectivity of the Marquette Method's hormonal monitoring. Women seeking the most direct connection to NaProTechnology diagnosis typically choose the Creighton Model. The SymptoThermal methods offer the redundancy of multiple biomarkers for confirmation.</p>

          <p>What matters most is that the method is learned from a trained instructor and charted consistently. The diagnostic value comes from the data. A well-kept chart gives the physician a window into hormonal function that no other tool can match.</p>

          <h3>Beyond Family Planning</h3>

          <p>FABMs are not just for couples trying to conceive or avoid pregnancy. Women who chart their cycles gain body literacy: an understanding of their own hormonal health that enables them to recognize when something changes. A cycle that was regular and suddenly becomes irregular is a signal. Premenstrual symptoms that worsen over time are a signal. These signals, captured on a chart, give physicians actionable data and give women an active role in their own healthcare.<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6e">6</a></sup></p>

          <p>This is why RRM physicians consider charting the foundation of their practice. It is the starting point for diagnosis, the tool for monitoring treatment response, and the long-term record of a woman's reproductive health. Without chart data, physicians cannot develop personalized testing protocols timed to a woman's individual cycle, and they lack the training to interpret the hormonal patterns that the data reveals. Most conventional OBGYNs simply do not have this information available. As Dr. Naomi Whittaker has described it, practicing reproductive medicine without cycle chart data is "flying blind."<sup><a href="#ref-7" id="cite-7e">7</a></sup></p>

          <!-- Section 6: Conditions Treated -->
