          <h3>Endometriosis</h3>

          <p>Endometriosis affects an estimated 10% of reproductive-age women. It is one of the most common causes of pelvic pain and infertility, and one of the most underdiagnosed. The median time from symptom onset to diagnosis is nine years.<sup><a href="#ref-13" id="cite-13b">13</a></sup> During those years, the disease progresses. Adhesions form. Fertility declines. Pain worsens. Many women are told their symptoms are normal or psychosomatic.</p>

          <p>The conventional approach relies on suppressive medications to manage pain. This masks symptoms without treating disease progression. When fertility is the goal, the conventional pathway bypasses the disease entirely with IVF. Neither approach addresses the endometriosis itself.</p>

          <p>RRM recommends minimally invasive excision surgery, which removes endometriosis tissue at the root rather than burning the surface (ablation). This distinction matters clinically. Ablation causes thermal damage and scarring to surrounding tissue, which compromises fertility. It also leaves disease behind, because ablation destroys only the visible surface while deeper implants persist. Dr. Patrick Yeung's ten-year surgical database shows a 2.5% repeat surgery rate after excision, compared to rates of up to 40% within one to two years after ablation.<sup><a href="#ref-11" id="cite-11c">11</a></sup></p>

          <p>Effective excision is more than cutting. Adhesion prevention using surgical membrane adhesion barriers (SMAP) is a critical component. Without adhesion prevention, scar tissue can reform after surgery, compromising both fertility and pain outcomes. Half of the surgical procedure is excision of the disease. The other half is reconstructive work and adhesion prevention protocols that preserve pelvic anatomy and reproductive function. Excision performed without these adjunctive techniques is less effective.</p>

          <p>After surgical excision of endometriosis, many women conceive through in vivo conception. No embryo laboratory. No high-dose ovarian stimulation. The disease is treated, and the body's own reproductive function is restored.</p>

          <p>Post-operative care includes hormonal support, cycle monitoring, and ongoing evaluation. This long-term management distinguishes RRM from a "surgery and done" approach. Endometriosis is a chronic condition. Treatment must account for that reality.</p>

          <h3>Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)</h3>

          <p>PCOS affects 6-12% of reproductive-age women. It is the most common endocrine disorder in this population. But not all PCOS is the same. The conventional approach often treats every case identically: suppressive medications to "regulate" cycles, followed by empiric ovulation induction when the couple wants to conceive.</p>

          <p>RRM evaluates PCOS by phenotype. Is insulin resistance the primary driver? Is there an inflammatory component? Is adrenal androgen overproduction involved? Did PCOS-like symptoms emerge after discontinuing suppressive medications (post-pill PCOS)? Each phenotype requires a different treatment strategy.</p>

          <p>Cycle charting reveals the specific ovulatory dysfunction present. Some women with PCOS ovulate irregularly. Others do not ovulate at all. Some have long cycles with delayed ovulation. The chart data guides the physician to the correct intervention: insulin-sensitizing agents for insulin-resistant PCOS, anti-inflammatory protocols for inflammatory subtypes, targeted ovulation support timed to the individual woman's cycle. Treatment follows from diagnosis, not from a one-size-fits-all protocol.<sup><a href="#ref-5" id="cite-5e">5</a></sup></p>

          <h3>Unexplained Infertility</h3>

          <p>"Unexplained infertility" is a label, not a diagnosis. It means the standard workup failed to find the cause. RRM reframes this as "not yet diagnosed" and begins a more thorough investigation.</p>

          <p>In practice, a cause is almost always found. Many couples labeled with unexplained infertility have undiagnosed endometriosis. Experienced excision surgeons report finding endometriosis in the majority of patients taken to diagnostic laparoscopy for pain and infertility.<sup><a href="#ref-13" id="cite-13c">13</a></sup> Others have luteal phase deficiency detectable only through serial post-peak progesterone testing, a deficiency invisible on a single day-21 blood draw. Some have subtle ovulatory dysfunction visible only on a well-charted cycle.</p>

          <p>The conventional pathway for unexplained infertility often bypasses investigation altogether. Couples are offered empiric IUI or IVF without anyone explaining why they could not conceive. RRM insists on answering that question first. The treatment works better when the target is known.<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6f">6</a></sup></p>

          <h3>Recurrent Miscarriage</h3>

          <p>Recurrent pregnancy loss, defined as two or more pregnancy losses, affects approximately 2 to 5% of couples trying to conceive. The conventional workup often includes karyotyping, antiphospholipid antibody testing, and uterine imaging. When these return normal, couples are told to "keep trying" or referred for IVF with preimplantation genetic testing (PGT-A).</p>

          <p>RRM expands the investigation. Progesterone support is a cornerstone, but in RRM it is timed to the ovulatory event identified on the cycle chart, not an arbitrary calendar date. Post-peak progesterone is measured serially (at peak +3, +5, +7, +9, +11) to identify luteal phase deficiency. Bio-identical progesterone supplementation is started at the correct time in the cycle and adjusted based on measured levels.<sup><a href="#ref-4" id="cite-4b">4</a></sup></p>

          <p>Full thyroid evaluation (including TPO antibodies, not just TSH) is standard. Immune factors, including natural killer cell activity and cytokine profiles, are evaluated when standard workups are negative. Anatomical assessment looks for uterine abnormalities, cervical insufficiency, and adhesions. RRM addresses the cause of pregnancy loss rather than moving directly to embryo selection in a laboratory.</p>

          <h3>Ovulatory Dysfunction</h3>

          <p>Ovulatory dysfunction encompasses anovulation (failure to ovulate), oligoovulation (infrequent ovulation), and luteal phase deficiency (ovulation occurs but the hormonal support afterward is inadequate). These conditions are common causes of both infertility and irregular cycles.</p>

          <p>Cycle charting is the key diagnostic tool. It reveals whether ovulation is occurring, when it occurs, and whether the post-ovulatory phase is adequate in length and quality. Without chart data, ovulatory dysfunction is often invisible to standard testing.</p>

          <p>Treatment is targeted. Women with anovulation receive ovulation support tailored to the underlying cause. Women with luteal phase deficiency receive bio-identical progesterone support, precisely timed to the post-peak phase. The response is monitored on the next cycle's chart. This cycle-by-cycle feedback loop allows continuous refinement of treatment, something that calendar-based protocols cannot achieve.<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9d">9</a></sup></p>

          <h3>Male Factor Infertility</h3>

          <p>A male factor is solely responsible in about 20% of infertile couples and is a contributing factor in another 30 to 40%.<sup><a href="#ref-27" id="cite-27e">27</a></sup> Despite this, the conventional fertility pathway often ignores the male partner entirely. When a semen analysis is abnormal, the standard recommendation is ICSI, an advanced laboratory procedure that injects a single sperm directly into an egg. ICSI bypasses the male condition without treating it, and shifts the entire treatment burden onto the woman.<sup><a href="#ref-12" id="cite-12d">12</a></sup></p>

          <p>RRM evaluates the male partner with the same cause-based approach applied to the female partner. Semen analysis is standard for every couple. When abnormalities are found, restorative andrology investigates the cause: hormonal imbalances (low testosterone, elevated FSH, prolactin disorders), varicocele, infections, oxidative stress, and metabolic factors. Treatment targets the specific cause. The goal is to restore sperm quality, not bypass the problem.</p>

          <h3>Irregular and Painful Periods, Pelvic Pain</h3>

          <p>Irregular periods, painful periods, and chronic pelvic pain are symptoms. They are not diagnoses. Each one signals an underlying condition that deserves investigation.</p>

          <p>The conventional approach too often skips the investigation. Suppressive medications are prescribed to eliminate the cycle, which eliminates the symptoms but hides the disease. Disease progression continues silently. When the woman discontinues the medication, the symptoms return, often worse than before, because the underlying condition was never treated.</p>

          <p>RRM performs a diagnostic workup. Cycle charting identifies hormonal patterns. Imaging evaluates structural causes. When endometriosis is suspected, diagnostic laparoscopy confirms and treats it. When hormonal imbalance is the cause, targeted support corrects it. The goal is treatment of the disease, not just management of pain.<sup><a href="#ref-7" id="cite-7b">7</a></sup></p>

          <h3>Premenstrual Syndrome (PMS) and PMDD</h3>

          <p>Premenstrual dysphoric disorder (PMDD) and severe PMS cause significant suffering. The conventional approach relies on SSRIs or suppressive medications. Both mask the underlying hormonal dysfunction.</p>

          <p>RRM evaluates hormonal levels across the cycle using the targeted panel timed to the cycle chart. Progesterone deficiency, estrogen-progesterone imbalance, and thyroid dysfunction are commonly identified contributors. Treatment uses bio-identical hormones targeted to the specific deficiency, timed to the correct phase of the cycle. Many women experience significant improvement when the hormonal cause is identified and treated rather than suppressed.<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9e">9</a></sup></p>

          <h3>Perimenopause and Menopausal Care</h3>

          <p>RRM does not end at fertility. The same diagnostic framework that identifies hormonal imbalances during the reproductive years applies to perimenopause and menopause. Cycle charting tracks the hormonal shifts that characterize the menopausal transition: lengthening cycles, erratic ovulation, declining progesterone, and changing mucus patterns. These observations guide treatment rather than waiting for symptoms to become severe.</p>

          <p>RRM physicians use bio-identical hormone support timed to the individual woman's cycle data during perimenopause and tailored to measured hormone levels during menopause. This differs from the conventional one-size-fits-all approach to hormone replacement therapy. Because RRM has already established each woman's hormonal baseline through years of cycle-charted data, the transition to perimenopausal and menopausal care is informed by a longitudinal record that most conventional practices do not have.</p>

          <h3>Whole-Body and Couple-Centered Care</h3>

          <p>RRM is more than a set of surgical and hormonal interventions. It is a whole-body, couple-centered approach to reproductive health. This distinguishes it from conventional fertility medicine, which focuses narrowly on achieving a pregnancy through a procedure.</p>

          <p><strong>Functional nutrition and metabolic health.</strong> Diet, gut health, and metabolic status directly affect hormonal balance, ovulatory function, and sperm quality. RRM physicians incorporate nutritional assessment into the diagnostic workup. Insulin resistance (a driver of PCOS), inflammatory markers, vitamin D status, thyroid cofactors, and oxidative stress are evaluated and addressed. Targeted nutritional interventions are part of the treatment plan, not an afterthought.</p>

          <p><strong>Functional bloodwork.</strong> The standard fertility workup checks a narrow set of hormones. RRM expands this to include a comprehensive metabolic and inflammatory panel: full thyroid (including free T3, free T4, reverse T3, and TPO antibodies), fasting insulin, hemoglobin A1c, inflammatory markers (CRP, ESR, homocysteine), vitamin D, ferritin, DHEA-S, and a complete metabolic profile. These tests identify systemic conditions that impair fertility and overall health but are invisible to a basic hormone panel.</p>

          <p><strong>Mental health and emotional support.</strong> Infertility and reproductive health conditions take a significant emotional toll. RRM acknowledges this as a clinical reality, not a secondary concern. Anxiety, depression, grief from pregnancy loss, and the relational strain of prolonged infertility are addressed as part of the care plan. Many RRM practices integrate counseling, support groups, or referrals to mental health professionals who understand the unique challenges of reproductive medicine. The couple is treated as a unit, not just the woman's reproductive system.</p>

          <p><strong>Environmental and lifestyle factors.</strong> Endocrine disruptors, environmental toxins, chronic stress, sleep disruption, and lifestyle factors affect both male and female fertility. RRM evaluates these exposures and addresses them as modifiable contributors to reproductive dysfunction. Reducing toxic load and optimizing the body's overall environment is part of creating the conditions for conception and healthy pregnancy.</p>

          <p><strong>Couple-centered healing.</strong> RRM treats the couple, not just the patient. Both partners are evaluated. Both partners are involved in treatment decisions. The charting process itself fosters shared understanding of the woman's cycle and creates a framework for communication about reproductive health. This collaborative model contrasts with IVF, where treatment is performed on the woman's body and the male partner's role is often limited to providing a semen sample. In RRM, healing is a shared journey.<sup><a href="#ref-7" id="cite-7d">7</a></sup></p>

          <aside class="callout-provider">
            <h3>For Healthcare Professionals</h3>
            <p>RRM treatment protocols are individualized by condition and cycle phase. For endometriosis, minimally invasive excision surgery combined with surgical membrane adhesion prevention (SMAP) and post-operative hormonal support is the standard. For PCOS, treatment depends on phenotype: insulin-resistant, inflammatory, adrenal, or post-pill. Luteal phase support uses bio-identical progesterone timed to post-peak days, not arbitrary calendar dates. For detailed protocols, see <a href="/courses/">RRM Academy clinical courses</a>.</p>
          </aside>

          <p><em>This content is for educational purposes only and does not constitute medical advice. Consult a qualified healthcare provider for diagnosis and treatment.</em></p>

          <!-- Section 7: RRM vs IVF -->
          <h2 id="rrm-vs-ivf">RRM vs. IVF: A Detailed Comparison</h2>

          <p>People search "RRM vs. IVF" because they want to understand how these approaches differ. This section exists to meet that question directly. But the framing matters. RRM is its own paradigm. It is not a stepping stone to IVF, a consolation prize for those who cannot afford IVF, or a religious alternative to IVF. It is a medical discipline that asks a different question.</p>

          <p>IVF asks: <em>How can we achieve a pregnancy?</em></p>
          <p>RRM asks: <em>Why can't this couple conceive, and can we fix it?</em></p>

          <p>These are fundamentally different starting points. They lead to different evaluations, different treatments, and different outcomes for the couple's overall health.</p>

