          <h3>The Cost Difference</h3>

          <p>Cost is one of the starkest differences. Katz et al. (2011) found that the average cost of IVF is 20 times greater than medication-only fertility treatments.<sup><a href="#ref-15" id="cite-15b">15</a></sup> IVF cycles typically range from $15,000 to $30,000, and many couples require multiple cycles. RRM treatments, particularly medication-based protocols, use standard pharmaceutical agents (progesterone, letrozole, hCG) that are a fraction of IVF drug costs. Many RRM evaluations and treatments are coded as treatment for diagnosed medical conditions, making them eligible for insurance coverage that IVF often does not receive.<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6g">6</a></sup></p>

          <h3>Obstetric Outcomes</h3>

          <p>RRM pregnancies are conceived in vivo. They are almost exclusively singletons. This matters for obstetric outcomes. Multiple pregnancies carry significantly higher risks of preterm delivery, low birth weight, NICU admission, and maternal complications including preeclampsia and hemorrhage.</p>

          <p>IVF pregnancies, particularly those involving multiple embryo transfer, carry elevated risks of multiple gestation. Even singleton IVF pregnancies are associated with higher rates of preterm delivery, low birth weight, and perinatal complications compared to spontaneously conceived singletons.<sup><a href="#ref-19" id="cite-19b">19</a></sup> RRM pregnancies do not carry these IVF-associated risks because conception occurs naturally after the underlying condition has been treated.</p>

          <h3>The IVF Evidence Gap</h3>

          <p>IVF is often presented as the gold standard of fertility treatment. The evidence base tells a more complicated story.</p>

          <p><strong>IVF success rates have not meaningfully improved in over two decades.</strong> Peer-reviewed analysis of CDC surveillance data shows that for fresh non-donor cycles, the live birth rate peaked at approximately 30% around 2010 and then declined to 22% by 2016, levels not seen since the late 1990s. Recent headline figures showing improvement (37% in 2022) reflect a methodological shift toward freeze-all protocols and frozen embryo transfers, not a breakthrough in underlying per-retrieval productivity.<sup><a href="#ref-31" id="cite-31">31</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-32" id="cite-32">32</a></sup></p>

          <p><strong>For unexplained infertility, there is insufficient evidence that IVF outperforms expectant management.</strong> The 2023 Cochrane systematic review of IVF for unexplained subfertility (Sunkara et al.) found only two randomized controlled trials with a combined 86 women and concluded that reviewers were "unable to draw any firm conclusions" about whether IVF is associated with higher live birth rates than trying naturally. A companion 2019 Cochrane network meta-analysis (Wang et al.) reached the same conclusion: "insufficient evidence of differences in live birth between expectant management and IVF/ICSI." Despite this, IVF is routinely offered as a first-line intervention for unexplained infertility after minimal evaluation.<sup><a href="#ref-33" id="cite-33">33</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-34" id="cite-34">34</a></sup></p>

          <p><strong>No randomized controlled trial has compared IVF to non-IVF treatment in women with PCOS or endometriosis.</strong> The 2023 International Evidence-based PCOS Guideline (co-endorsed by ASRM and ESHRE) explicitly states that it "did not identify any published RCTs comparing IVF treatment with ovulation induction treatments or placebo/no treatment in PCOS." Its IVF recommendation is classified as a Clinical Consensus Recommendation, not evidence-based. For endometriosis, the ESHRE 2022 guideline acknowledges the same gap: "many clinical decision points have not been evaluated in RCTs."<sup><a href="#ref-35" id="cite-35">35</a></sup> IVF use for the two most common reproductive conditions is based on clinical consensus and observational data, not RCT evidence of superiority over alternatives.</p>

          <p>None of this means IVF does not work. It means the evidence base supporting IVF as the default pathway for these conditions is far weaker than patients are typically told. When a treatment lacks RCT evidence, that applies to IVF as much as it applies to RRM.</p>

          <h3>RRM After Failed IVF</h3>

          <p>RRM can help couples who have already undergone failed IVF cycles. Because IVF bypasses the underlying condition, that condition remains after IVF fails. RRM identifies and treats it.</p>

          <p>Boyle et al. (2022) reported a case of successful pregnancy achieved through RRM after 16 years of infertility, three recurrent miscarriages, and eight unsuccessful embryo transfers with IVF/ICSI. The RRM evaluation identified treatable conditions that the IVF pathway had never investigated. After targeted treatment, the couple conceived naturally and delivered a healthy singleton.<sup><a href="#ref-10" id="cite-10b">10</a></sup></p>

          <p>Boyle et al. (2018) published the most detailed study on this question in <em>Frontiers in Medicine</em>. Among 403 couples who had already failed an average of 2.1 IVF cycles, RRM achieved a life-table live birth rate of 32.1%. Of the 74 live births, only one was a twin (1.4%), and 92% were born at term (37+ weeks).<sup><a href="#ref-17" id="cite-17">17</a></sup> These results demonstrate that RRM is not simply an alternative to IVF. It finds and treats conditions that IVF never investigates. For couples who have been told "IVF is your only option" and it has not worked, RRM offers a fundamentally different path.</p>

          <h3>When IVF May Be Appropriate</h3>

          <p>RRM cannot help every couple. Bilateral tubal occlusion (both fallopian tubes are blocked or absent) prevents egg transport regardless of hormonal health. Severe male factor infertility, such as azoospermia (no sperm in the ejaculate), may require assisted reproduction when no treatable cause can be identified. When time is a critical factor and the couple makes a fully informed choice, IVF may be the right path.</p>

          <p>Honest medicine requires acknowledging these limits. RRM physicians do so. What distinguishes RRM is the insistence that treatable conditions should be treated first, not bypassed, and that couples deserve a thorough evaluation before being directed to procedures that do not address their underlying health.</p>

          <h3>A Note on IVF Outcome Reporting</h3>

          <p>In the United States, SART membership is voluntary, and SART serves as the primary data intermediary for the CDC's National ART Surveillance System (NASS). A 2013 analysis in <em>Fertility and Sterility</em> found that 13 clinics (3.8% of U.S. fertility centers) accounted for half of all cycles excluded from SART reporting; those clinics published above-average success rates and grew their market share by 19.9%.<sup><a href="#ref-30" id="cite-30">30</a></sup> HFEA data from the United Kingdom provides a more comprehensive picture because reporting is mandatory for all licensed clinics. HFEA data shows an average live birth rate of approximately 33% per embryo transferred for women under 35, with rates declining significantly with age: approximately 25% for ages 35-37, 17% for ages 38-39, and under 10% for women over 42.<sup><a href="#ref-16" id="cite-16e">16</a></sup></p>

          <p><a href="/courses/rrm-vs-ivf/">Learn more in our free course: RRM vs. Standard ART</a>.</p>

          <!-- Section 8: Evidence -->
          <h2 id="evidence">The Evidence Behind RRM</h2>

          <p>RRM is supported by peer-reviewed research published in journals including the <em>Journal of the American Board of Family Medicine</em>, <em>Canadian Family Physician</em>, the <em>Journal of Medical Case Reports</em>, <em>Frontiers in Medicine</em>, and <em>Fertility and Sterility</em>. The <a href="https://library.rrmacademy.org">RRM Academy Research Library</a> contains 3,000+ peer-reviewed publications covering RRM outcomes, surgical techniques, hormonal protocols, and fertility awareness-based methods.</p>

          <p>This section organizes the existing evidence by category, presents it transparently, and acknowledges the current limitations of the research base. Intellectual honesty is essential. The evidence supports RRM. It also has gaps. Both facts matter.</p>

          <h3>RRM Outcomes Studies</h3>

          <p><strong>Stanford et al. (2008)</strong> published the landmark RRM outcomes study in the <em>Journal of the American Board of Family Medicine</em>. This prospective cohort study followed couples treated with NaProTechnology in an Irish general practice. Among couples with infertility treated over 24 months, the study reported a crude live birth rate of 25.5% and a Kaplan-Meier adjusted cumulative rate of 52.8%. Younger women and those with lower BMI had the highest success rates. The study also documented improvements in gynecological health independent of pregnancy outcomes.<sup><a href="#ref-3" id="cite-3d">3</a></sup></p>

          <p><strong>Tham et al. (2012)</strong> studied NaProTechnology outcomes at a Canadian family practice and published results in <em>Canadian Family Physician</em>. Among couples with infertility, 38% achieved at least one live birth. Among women with recurrent miscarriage, those treated with RRM protocols had significantly improved outcomes compared to their prior pregnancy histories. The study demonstrated that RRM could be effectively delivered in a primary care setting, not only in specialized fertility clinics.<sup><a href="#ref-4" id="cite-4d">4</a></sup></p>

          <p><strong>James et al. (2021, preprint)</strong> reported pregnancy outcomes from a restorative infertility treatment model at a single Australian centre on medRxiv. The study followed 164 couples and reported a crude live birth rate of 35.4% and an adjusted cumulative rate of 57.4% at 24 months.<sup><a href="#ref-18" id="cite-18">18</a></sup></p>

          <p><strong>Stanford et al. (2021)</strong> published a peer-reviewed study in <em>BMC Pregnancy and Childbirth</em> covering two New England family medicine clinics. The study reported a 29% cumulative live birth rate at two years among couples treated with NaProTechnology-based restorative reproductive medicine.<sup><a href="#ref-28" id="cite-28">28</a></sup></p>

          <p><strong>Boyle et al. (2022)</strong> reported a detailed case study in the <em>Journal of Medical Case Reports</em> documenting successful pregnancy after 16 years of infertility, three recurrent miscarriages, and eight failed IVF/ICSI embryo transfers. The couple conceived naturally and delivered a healthy singleton after RRM evaluation identified and treated the underlying conditions.<sup><a href="#ref-10" id="cite-10c">10</a></sup></p>

          <p><strong>Boyle et al. (2018)</strong> published a cohort study in <em>Frontiers in Medicine</em> reporting healthy singleton pregnancies achieved through RRM after previous failed IVF. Among 403 couples with an average of 2.1 prior IVF attempts, the life-table live birth rate was 32.1%. Only 1 of 74 live births was a twin (1.4%), and 92% were born at 37+ weeks.<sup><a href="#ref-17" id="cite-17b">17</a></sup></p>

          <p><strong>Boyle et al. (2025)</strong> published the first head-to-head RRM-versus-IVF comparison in the inaugural volume of the <em>Journal of Restorative Reproductive Medicine</em>. In a retrospective evaluation of 187 couples treated at NeoFertility Dublin in 2019, the crude live birth rate was 41% (77/187). The conception rate was 52%. Prematurity in singletons was 4.0%, compared to 11.8% in CDC data and 14.4% in SART-reported IVF singletons. Average time to conception was 12 months.<sup><a href="#ref-24" id="cite-24e">24</a></sup></p>

