          <h3>Surgical Outcomes</h3>

          <p>Endometriosis excision surgery is one of the most studied interventions in RRM. Post-excision pregnancy rates depend on disease severity, surgical completeness, and individual patient factors. These pregnancies are achieved through in vivo conception after the disease is treated.</p>

          <p>Long-term surgical outcomes distinguish excision from ablation. Yeung et al. (2024), published in <em>Acta Scientific Women's Health</em>, reported a 2.5% rate of repeat surgery over ten years following optimal excision of endometriosis at a single tertiary referral center (620 patients). Sutton et al. (1994) reported repeat surgery rates of up to 40% at one to two years after laser ablation.<sup><a href="#ref-11" id="cite-11e">11</a></sup> This difference is clinically significant. Excision removes the disease. Ablation burns the surface. The distinction determines whether women face repeated surgeries or sustained relief.</p>

          <h3>Cost-Effectiveness</h3>

          <p>Katz et al. (2011) conducted a prospective 18-month cohort study published in <em>Fertility and Sterility</em> and found that the average cost of IVF was 20 times greater than medication-only fertility treatments.<sup><a href="#ref-15" id="cite-15c">15</a></sup> A single IVF cycle costs $15,000 to $30,000 in the United States. Most couples need two to three cycles, bringing average total costs to $40,000 to $60,000 or more. In the United States, only a minority of states mandate insurance coverage for IVF, leaving most couples to pay out of pocket.</p>

          <p>RRM treatments, because they diagnose and treat specific medical conditions, are often coded under standard diagnostic and treatment categories that insurance already covers: laparoscopy for endometriosis, hormonal testing for endocrine evaluation, progesterone for luteal phase support. This structural insurance advantage means that RRM is accessible to many couples who cannot afford IVF's cash-pay model.<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6h">6</a></sup></p>

          <h3>Obstetric Outcomes</h3>

          <p>RRM pregnancies are achieved through in vivo conception and are almost exclusively singletons. This confers significant obstetric advantages. Multiple gestation pregnancies, which are more common with IVF (particularly with multiple embryo transfer), carry elevated risks of preterm delivery, low birth weight, cerebral palsy, and neonatal death.</p>

          <p>Even singleton IVF pregnancies are associated with higher rates of adverse obstetric outcomes compared to spontaneously conceived singletons. HFEA data documents higher rates of preterm birth, low birth weight, and perinatal complications among IVF-conceived pregnancies.<sup><a href="#ref-16" id="cite-16f">16</a></sup> Bewley et al. (2011) reviewed adverse outcomes from IVF and documented increased risks of ectopic pregnancy, preeclampsia, placenta previa, and cesarean delivery.<sup><a href="#ref-19" id="cite-19">19</a></sup></p>

          <p>RRM pregnancies, because they result from in vivo conception after the underlying condition has been treated, do not carry these procedure-associated risks. The mother's health is also improved because the underlying disease has been addressed, reducing the risk of complications from untreated conditions like endometriosis or hormonal deficiency during pregnancy.</p>

          <h3>Honest Assessment of Limitations</h3>

          <p>The current RRM evidence base has real limitations, and acknowledging them is part of practicing honest medicine.</p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Study design.</strong> Most RRM studies are observational cohort studies or case series, not randomized controlled trials (RCTs). This is a legitimate methodological limitation. It is also a limitation shared by much of IVF research. RCTs are difficult to conduct in fertility medicine for ethical and practical reasons.</li>
            <li><strong>Sample sizes.</strong> RRM studies involve smaller cohorts than IVF mega-databases. The RRM research base is growing, but it does not yet match the volume of IVF-related publications.</li>
            <li><strong>A young field.</strong> RRM as a formalized discipline is relatively young. NaProTechnology has been practiced since the 1980s, but the broader RRM framework with standardized protocols and international collaboration emerged more recently. More research is needed and is actively underway.</li>
            <li><strong>Not a solution for every couple.</strong> RRM cannot help couples with bilateral tubal occlusion (both tubes blocked or absent) or severe male factor infertility such as azoospermia when no treatable cause is found. These are cases where assisted reproductive technology may be the only option for biological parenthood.</li>
            <li><strong>Publication bias.</strong> Publication bias exists in all fertility research, including IVF. Clinics and researchers are more likely to publish favorable outcomes. This affects the interpretation of all fertility statistics, not just RRM data. The HFEA's mandatory reporting in the United Kingdom provides the most complete IVF outcome data available precisely because it eliminates selective reporting.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>A Note on the Criticism</h3>

          <p>In 2025 and 2026, professional organizations including ACOG and ASRM published position statements, editorials, and open letters criticizing RRM. A review of these documents reveals a pattern: the critiques are structural (no RCTs, no ABMS sub-board, ideological framing) rather than data-driven. The ACOG Issue Brief on RRM, the ASRM "Just the Facts" sheet, the ASRM letter to IIRRM, and the joint open letter to the National Governors Association collectively cite zero peer-reviewed RRM outcome studies to support the claim that RRM lacks evidence. A January 2026 JAMA Viewpoint authored by a graduate of ASRM's PRIMED advocacy training program similarly engages with policy arguments without citing or refuting any specific RRM clinical data.</p>

          <p>The publicly available advocacy documents reviewed here do not cite or engage with Boyle et al. (2018), Boyle et al. (2025), Sanchez-Mendez et al. (2025), or James et al. (2021).<sup><a href="#ref-28" id="cite-28b">28</a></sup> The newest and largest data in the field is unaddressed.</p>

          <p>This does not mean the criticism is baseless. The call for RCTs is legitimate. The concern about patient access to IVF is real. But patients and providers deserve to evaluate the actual published data, not a characterization of the field that ignores it.</p>

          <h3>Why This Field Needs to Exist</h3>

          <p>RRM did not emerge in a vacuum. It exists because of structural gaps in how reproductive medicine is taught, funded, and practiced.</p>

          <p><strong>Training gaps.</strong> An evaluation of 20 U.S. medical school curricula found that fertility awareness-based methods account for just 4% of all family planning mentions, compared to nine times more coverage for hormonal contraception. Only 4% of practicing physicians have received any formal FABM training, and over 80% of family medicine residents report receiving less than one hour of FABM education during their entire residency.<sup><a href="#ref-5" id="cite-5f">5</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-36" id="cite-36">36</a></sup> When physicians are not trained to read cycle data, they cannot use it diagnostically. The result is an entire generation of OBGYNs who default to suppressive medications because they were never taught an alternative framework. That over-reliance on suppression has stalled the kind of clinical curiosity that drives medical progress in other fields.<sup><a href="#ref-7" id="cite-7g">7</a></sup></p>

          <p><strong>Research funding.</strong> Women's health research has been systematically underfunded relative to disease burden. A 2021 analysis in the <em>Journal of Women's Health</em> found that in approximately 74% of sex-skewed diseases, NIH funding favors male-prevalent conditions. Endometriosis receives 18 cents per dollar of what its disease burden warrants. PCOS receives $9 to $10 million per year from NIH despite affecting 13% of reproductive-age women. A 2024 National Academies of Sciences report found that only 8.8% of NIH grant spending from 2013 to 2023 targeted women's health research, and that share has been declining even as the overall NIH budget has grown.<sup><a href="#ref-37" id="cite-37">37</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-38" id="cite-38">38</a></sup></p>

          <p><strong>Technology without science.</strong> The growing "femtech" industry promises women data-driven reproductive health tools, but much of the underlying science has not been validated against the established biomarker research that RRM physicians rely on.<sup><a href="#ref-7" id="cite-7h">7</a></sup> Cycle-tracking apps that estimate ovulation from algorithms without validated biomarker inputs are not equivalent to clinically validated charting methods taught by trained instructors. RRM Academy is developing resources to help women evaluate femtech products against the published evidence base.</p>

          <p>The existing evidence supports RRM as an effective, safe, and cost-effective approach for the majority of couples facing infertility and reproductive health conditions. It also demonstrates that RRM improves the health of women and men even when pregnancy is not achieved. Couples who go through the RRM process leave with a diagnosis, a treatment record, and an understanding of their own bodies that no one can take away. Even when the outcome is not a baby, patients consistently report that having answers, knowing why, changes everything.<sup><a href="#ref-7" id="cite-7f">7</a></sup> The field needs more large-scale prospective studies, and organizations like FACTS About Fertility and the IIRRM are working to make that happen.</p>

          <p><em>Outcomes vary by individual. All statistics cited represent published research averages, not guarantees of individual results.</em></p>

          <!-- Section 9: Patient Journey -->
          <h2 id="patient-journey">What to Expect: The RRM Patient Journey</h2>

          <p>No competitor in reproductive medicine has published a clear walkthrough of the RRM process. That gap ends here. Below is what couples can expect from start to finish.</p>

          <ol>
            <li>
              <strong>Learn to chart (1-3 cycles).</strong>
              <p>A woman learns a validated cycle-charting method from a trained instructor. Creighton Model, Marquette, FEMM, and Billings are the most common systems used in RRM. This charting provides the baseline diagnostic data that drives every decision downstream. Some RRM physicians accept a woman who has just begun learning to chart. Others prefer two to three completed cycles before the first appointment. Either way, the chart is the foundation.<sup><a href="#ref-7" id="cite-7c">7</a></sup></p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Initial consultation.</strong>
              <p>The physician reviews the chart data alongside a full medical history. Both partners attend. The conversation covers symptoms, reproductive goals, prior treatments, and what the chart reveals about cycle length, ovulation timing, mucus patterns, and hormonal signals. For many women, this is the first time a physician has interpreted their cycle data as a diagnostic tool rather than asking only about period dates.<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2c">2</a></sup></p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Diagnostic workup (1-3 months).</strong>
              <p>Testing is targeted, not scattershot. Hormonal panels are timed to specific cycle days based on each woman's chart. Imaging studies assess uterine and ovarian anatomy. A semen analysis evaluates the male partner. If endometriosis is suspected, the physician may recommend diagnostic laparoscopy with excision. The evaluation is thorough and systematic. Every test is ordered because the chart pointed to a specific question that needs answering.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Diagnosis and treatment plan.</strong>
              <p>A specific diagnosis (or multiple diagnoses) is identified. "Unexplained infertility" is not an acceptable endpoint. It simply means the evaluation is not finished. Treatment is matched to findings: cycle-timed hormonal support, targeted medication, surgical excision, nutritional optimization, or a combination. The plan is individualized. Two women with the same symptom may receive entirely different protocols because their underlying causes differ.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Ongoing monitoring (3-12+ months).</strong>
              <p>Treatment response is tracked cycle by cycle through the chart and follow-up labs. Biomarker changes show whether the protocol is working in real time. If mucus patterns improve, if the luteal phase lengthens, if hormone levels normalize, the data confirms progress. If not, the physician adjusts. This is not "try and see." It is iterative, data-driven care where every cycle generates actionable information.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Outcomes.</strong>
              <p>For couples seeking fertility, the physician provides conception support and early pregnancy monitoring, including progesterone supplementation when indicated. For women not pursuing pregnancy, the goal is sustained symptom relief and prevention of disease progression. Either way, the woman leaves with a diagnosis, a treatment record, and knowledge about her own body that no one can take away.</p>
            </li>
          </ol>

          <p><strong>Set realistic expectations.</strong> RRM is not a quick fix. Most couples should expect a timeline of 6 to 18 months from first appointment to resolution, depending on diagnosis complexity. Some conditions require surgery followed by months of post-operative hormonal management before conception is attempted. The process is thorough because it has to be. Shortcuts lead to the same dead ends that brought most couples to RRM in the first place.</p>

          <!-- Section 10: Cost and Insurance -->
          <h2 id="cost-insurance">How Much Does RRM Cost?</h2>

          <p>Cost is one of the most common questions couples ask. The answer matters because it shapes who can access care.</p>

          <p>IVF costs $15,000 to $30,000 per cycle in the United States, including medications and monitoring. Most couples need two to three cycles to achieve a live birth, bringing average total out-of-pocket spending to $40,000 to $60,000. Costs rise substantially for older patients and with add-ons like genetic testing (PGT-A), ICSI, and frozen embryo transfers. The Katz et al. prospective cohort study found that IVF costs on average 20 times more than medication-based fertility treatments.<sup><a href="#ref-15" id="cite-15b">15</a></sup></p>

          <p>RRM costs vary by diagnosis and treatment plan. The key structural advantage is that RRM treats diagnosed medical conditions using standard diagnostic and treatment codes. Charting instruction, hormonal panels, medications, and surgery for conditions like endometriosis or PCOS use the same CPT codes any specialist would bill. This means many components of RRM care are covered by standard health insurance, without requiring a separate "fertility treatment" benefit. By contrast, IVF is typically classified as elective fertility treatment and covered by insurance in only a minority of U.S. states, leaving most couples to pay out of pocket.<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6i">6</a></sup></p>

          <h3>Insurance Coverage</h3>

          <p>Many RRM treatments are covered by insurance because they are coded as treatment for diagnosed medical conditions, not as "fertility treatment." Endometriosis surgery uses standard surgical codes. Thyroid treatment uses endocrine codes. PCOS management uses metabolic and gynecologic codes. The diagnostic workup uses the same CPT codes any specialist would bill. This is a significant advantage. When a condition has a diagnostic code, insurance pays for its treatment regardless of whether the patient is also trying to conceive.</p>

          <h3>Legislative Progress</h3>

          <p>The policy landscape is shifting. In 2025, Arkansas became the first state to mandate insurance coverage for restorative reproductive medicine.<sup><a href="#ref-12" id="cite-12b">12</a></sup> The RESTORE Act (H.R. 3589), introduced in the 119th Congress, seeks to expand federal access to RRM as an alternative to IVF coverage mandates.<sup><a href="#ref-20" id="cite-20">20</a></sup> The national debate over IVF policy, including the Trump administration's February 2025 executive order on IVF access, has created new visibility for cause-based approaches and raised the question of whether they deserve equal standing in coverage mandates.</p>

          <h3>What to Ask Your Insurer</h3>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Ask about diagnostic coverage.</strong> "Is cycle-timed hormonal testing covered under my plan when ordered for a diagnosed condition such as PCOS, endometriosis, or luteal phase defect?"</li>
            <li><strong>Ask about surgical coverage.</strong> "Is laparoscopic excision surgery for endometriosis covered as a gynecologic procedure, separate from any fertility benefit?"</li>
            <li><strong>Ask about out-of-network benefits.</strong> Many RRM physicians are not in-network for every plan. Out-of-network benefits may still cover a significant portion of costs.</li>
            <li><strong>Ask about your state's mandates.</strong> Some states require coverage for fertility diagnosis or treatment. RRM treatments often qualify under these mandates because they treat medical conditions, not just infertility as a standalone diagnosis.</li>
          </ul>

          <!-- Section 11: NaProTechnology -->
          <h2 id="naprotechnology">NaProTechnology: What It Is and How It Works</h2>

          <p>NaProTechnology (Natural Procreative Technology) is the most established clinical system within restorative reproductive medicine. Understanding three distinct terms clarifies how the pieces fit together:</p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Creighton Model FertilityCare System (CrMS)</strong> is the fertility charting system. A trained FertilityCare Practitioner teaches a woman to observe and record specific biomarkers, primarily cervical mucus patterns, across each cycle. The result is a standardized chart that maps hormonal activity in real time.</li>
            <li><strong>NaProTechnology</strong> is the medical and surgical application built on Creighton Model data. Physicians use the chart to time diagnostic tests, identify abnormalities, and guide treatment. NaPro includes hormonal evaluation protocols, cycle-timed medication, and advanced surgical techniques focused on reproductive organ preservation.</li>
            <li><strong>RRM</strong> is the broader medical discipline that emerged in the 2000s. NaProTechnology predates the RRM umbrella by two decades and maintains its own institutional identity through the Pope Paul VI Institute. Other systems, including FEMM (Fertility Education and Medical Management), NeoFertility, and Marquette-based protocols, also practice cause-directed reproductive medicine. They share the same root-cause philosophy but differ in charting methods and clinical frameworks.</li>
          </ul>

          <p>Dr. Thomas Hilgers developed NaProTechnology at the Pope Paul VI Institute in Omaha, Nebraska, beginning in the 1980s. His prospective studies tracking women's hormones throughout their cycles established precise reference ranges for progesterone, estradiol, and other hormones at each phase of the cycle, giving NaPro physicians a diagnostic framework that most conventional training does not provide.<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9b">9</a></sup></p>

          <h3>Is NaProTechnology Only for Catholics?</h3>

          <p>No. NaProTechnology was developed in a Catholic institutional context. The Pope Paul VI Institute is named for the pope who wrote <em>Humanae Vitae</em>. That history is real. But the clinical protocols are based on human physiology, not theology. Cervical mucus behaves the same way regardless of a woman's religious beliefs. Progesterone levels follow the same patterns. Endometriosis does not discriminate by faith.</p>

          <p>Both Catholic and non-Catholic patients seek NaProTechnology because they want a thorough diagnostic workup, cause-based treatment, and a physician who will not default to suppressive medications as a first-line response. The medicine works because it is grounded in biology. Any patient can benefit regardless of religious background.<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2d">2</a></sup></p>

          <h3>Physician Training</h3>

          <p>NaProTechnology physicians complete fellowship training at the Pope Paul VI Institute or equivalent programs recognized by the IIRRM. Fellowship includes advanced surgical training (including excision of endometriosis and reconstructive procedures), hormonal evaluation and cycle-timed prescribing, and integration of Creighton Model data into clinical decision-making. These physicians hold board certification in OBGYN, family medicine, or reproductive endocrinology in addition to their NaPro credentials.</p>

          <p><a href="/courses/masterclass-in-endometriosis-and-surgery/">Learn from a NaProTechnology-trained surgeon: Masterclass in Endometriosis &amp; Surgery</a></p>

          <!-- Section 12: Training and Credentials -->
          <h2 id="training">RRM Training and Credentials for Healthcare Professionals</h2>

          <p>RRM is a growing field. The training landscape includes pathways for charting instructors, physicians, medical students, and allied health professionals. Here is how the ecosystem is structured.</p>

          <h3>1. FertilityCare Practitioner (FCP)</h3>

          <p>A FertilityCare Practitioner teaches patients to chart using the Creighton Model FertilityCare System. Certification is through the American Academy of FertilityCare Professionals (AAFCP). The education program spans 13 months and includes didactic coursework, supervised practicum, and competency evaluation. FCPs are the front line of RRM. They provide the charting instruction that generates the diagnostic data physicians depend on.</p>

          <h3>2. Medical Consultant</h3>

          <p>A Medical Consultant is a physician who interprets Creighton Model charts and manages medical and surgical treatment. Certification requires completion of fellowship training and demonstrated competency in cycle-based evaluation, hormonal assessment, and NaProTechnology protocols. Medical Consultants diagnose conditions, prescribe cycle-timed medications, and perform or refer for surgical intervention.</p>

          <h3>3. NaProTechnology Fellowship</h3>

          <p>Advanced training is available through the Pope Paul VI Institute and allied programs. Fellowship covers surgical techniques (including endometriosis excision, adhesion prevention, and tubal reconstruction), hormonal evaluation protocols, and the full scope of cycle-based care. This is the most intensive credential in the field and produces physicians capable of managing complex, multi-system reproductive conditions.</p>

          <h3>4. RRM Academy</h3>

          <p>RRM Academy (<a href="/courses/">rrmacademy.org</a>) is an online education platform offering courses for both patients and healthcare professionals. Course topics include endometriosis, surgical technique, postpartum health, and the fundamentals of restorative reproductive medicine. RRM Academy bridges the gap between fellowship-level expertise and the broader medical community by making specialized knowledge accessible through structured online coursework.</p>

          <h3>5. FEMM and RHRI (Reproductive Health Research Institute)</h3>

          <p>FEMM's research arm, the Reproductive Health Research Institute (RHRI), provides Medical Management training for physicians. The program covers differential diagnosis and treatment of hormonal disorders including ovulatory dysfunction, PCOS, thyroid imbalances, and infertility using standardized clinical protocols developed under Dr. Pilar Vigil at the Pontifical Catholic University of Chile. Training is available through in-person courses and on-demand online formats at <a href="https://femmhealth.org/professional-education/" rel="noopener">femmhealth.org</a>.</p>

          <h3>6. FACTS (Fertility Appreciation Collaborative to Teach the Science)</h3>

          <p>FACTS offers a medical elective for students and residents that introduces fertility awareness-based methods and restorative reproductive medicine into clinical training. The elective provides CME credit and is designed to integrate into existing medical education curricula. FACTS also hosts an annual conference, community case discussions, and a professional CME course for practicing physicians.<sup><a href="#ref-21" id="cite-21">21</a></sup></p>

          <h3>7. IIRRM (International Institute for Restorative Reproductive Medicine)</h3>

          <p>The IIRRM provides international credentialing, hosts conferences, facilitates case study discussions, and maintains a provider referral network. It serves as the professional home for the global RRM community, connecting physicians, researchers, and educators across countries and practice settings.<sup><a href="#ref-1" id="cite-1b">1</a></sup></p>

          <aside class="callout-provider">
            <h3>For Healthcare Professionals</h3>
            <p>If you are a physician interested in adding RRM to your practice, start with <a href="/courses/">RRM Academy's clinical courses</a>. For formal credentialing, contact the <a href="https://iirrm.org" rel="noopener">IIRRM</a> or explore fellowship opportunities through the Pope Paul VI Institute. <a href="https://femmhealth.org/professional-education/" rel="noopener">RHRI/FEMM</a> offers Medical Management training in hormonal protocols. FACTS offers a <a href="https://www.factsaboutfertility.org" rel="noopener">medical elective</a> for students and residents. No matter your starting point, cycle-based evaluation can be integrated into any OBGYN, family medicine, or endocrinology practice.</p>
          </aside>

          <!-- Section 13: Common Myths About RRM -->
          <h2 id="myths">Common Myths About Restorative Reproductive Medicine</h2>

          <p>RRM challenges assumptions that many patients and physicians take for granted. That generates pushback. Some of it comes from genuine misunderstanding. Some comes from professional organizations with competing interests. The myths below represent the most common objections. Each one collapses under scrutiny.</p>

          <div class="myth-fact">
            <span class="myth-label">Myth</span>
            <p class="myth-text">"RRM is only for religious people."</p>
            <span class="fact-label">Fact</span>
            <p class="fact-text">RRM is a medical discipline practiced by board-certified physicians. The science does not depend on any religious framework. NaProTechnology was developed at a Catholic institution, but its protocols are based on reproductive physiology, not theology. Patients of all backgrounds and beliefs seek RRM for the same reason: thorough diagnosis and cause-based treatment. No faith commitment is required to benefit from having your hormones tested, your endometriosis excised, or your luteal phase supported.<sup><a href="#ref-1" id="cite-1c">1</a></sup></p>
          </div>

          <div class="myth-fact">
            <span class="myth-label">Myth</span>
            <p class="myth-text">"RRM is alternative medicine."</p>
            <span class="fact-label">Fact</span>
            <p class="fact-text">RRM uses standard medical tools: bloodwork, imaging, laparoscopy, pharmacology. Its physicians are board-certified OBGYNs and reproductive endocrinologists trained at accredited medical institutions. The difference is in how and when those tools are applied. RRM times interventions to each cycle phase and targets the diagnosed cause. Published research appears in peer-reviewed journals including the <em>Journal of the American Board of Family Medicine</em>, <em>Canadian Family Physician</em>, <em>Frontiers in Medicine</em>, and the <em>Journal of Medical Case Reports</em>.<sup><a href="#ref-3" id="cite-3c">3</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-4" id="cite-4c">4</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-17" id="cite-17b">17</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-10" id="cite-10b">10</a></sup> That is the definition of evidence-based medicine.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="myth-fact">
            <span class="myth-label">Myth</span>
            <p class="myth-text">"RRM only works for infertility."</p>
            <span class="fact-label">Fact</span>
            <p class="fact-text">RRM treats endometriosis, PCOS, pelvic pain, hormonal imbalances, irregular periods, PMS, and PMDD regardless of fertility goals. Many women seek RRM with no desire to conceive. They want answers. They want their symptoms diagnosed and treated rather than masked with suppressive medications. Cycle-based evaluation is useful for any woman who wants to understand her hormonal health. Fertility is one application. It is not the only one.<sup><a href="#ref-5" id="cite-5c">5</a></sup></p>
          </div>

          <div class="myth-fact">
            <span class="myth-label">Myth</span>
            <p class="myth-text">"RRM has no evidence base."</p>
            <span class="fact-label">Fact</span>
            <p class="fact-text">Published studies document RRM outcomes in <em>JABFM</em>, <em>Canadian Family Physician</em>, <em>Frontiers in Medicine</em>, the <em>Journal of Medical Case Reports</em>, and the <em>Journal of Restorative Reproductive Medicine</em>. Stanford, Parnell, and Boyle reported crude live birth rates of 26% (adjusted: 53%) after NaProTechnology treatment in an Irish general practice.<sup><a href="#ref-3" id="cite-3d">3</a></sup> Tham, Schliep, and Stanford reported a 38% crude live birth rate in a Canadian cohort.<sup><a href="#ref-4" id="cite-4d">4</a></sup> Boyle et al. (2025) reported a 41% live birth rate in 187 couples at NeoFertility Dublin.<sup><a href="#ref-24" id="cite-24b">24</a></sup> Boyle et al. (2018) demonstrated healthy singleton pregnancies from RRM after multiple failed IVF cycles.<sup><a href="#ref-17" id="cite-17c">17</a></sup> The <a href="https://library.rrmacademy.org">RRM Research Library</a> indexes over 3,000 publications relevant to restorative reproductive medicine. More research is needed, and more is underway. But claiming there is "no evidence" ignores what already exists.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="myth-fact">
            <span class="myth-label">Myth</span>
            <p class="myth-text">"RRM is anti-IVF."</p>
            <span class="fact-label">Fact</span>
            <p class="fact-text">RRM is its own medical paradigm. It does not define itself in opposition to any other approach. RRM focuses on identifying and treating the condition that causes reproductive dysfunction. Some couples choose IVF after completing an RRM evaluation. Others find that once the underlying disease is treated, they conceive without assisted reproduction. The goal is diagnosis and treatment. What the couple decides to do with that information is their decision.<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6c">6</a></sup></p>
          </div>

          <div class="myth-fact">
            <span class="myth-label">Myth</span>
            <p class="myth-text">"You need to choose between RRM and conventional medicine."</p>
            <span class="fact-label">Fact</span>
            <p class="fact-text">RRM IS conventional medicine. Same diagnostic tools. Same surgical techniques. Same pharmacology. Same board-certified physicians. The distinction is the clinical approach: identify the cause first, then treat it. RRM physicians work within the standard medical system, order labs through standard reference laboratories, perform surgery in accredited hospitals, and prescribe FDA-approved medications. There is nothing to choose between. RRM is what thorough, cause-based conventional medicine looks like when applied to reproductive health.<sup><a href="#ref-7" id="cite-7c">7</a></sup></p>
          </div>

          <!-- Section 14: How to Get Started -->
          <h2 id="get-started">How to Get Started with Restorative Reproductive Medicine</h2>

          <p>Getting started depends on who you are and what you need. Below are three pathways: one for couples and individuals seeking care, one for healthcare professionals, and one for researchers.</p>

          <h3>For Couples and Individuals</h3>

          <ol>
            <li><strong>Learn a validated cycle-charting method.</strong> Charting provides the diagnostic data that RRM physicians rely on. Options include the Creighton Model FertilityCare System, Marquette Method, FEMM, Billings Ovulation Method, and SymptoThermal methods. Find a local instructor through <a href="https://www.fertilitycare.org" rel="noopener">FertilityCare Centers of America</a> or the training organization for your chosen method. Most couples need 1 to 3 charted cycles before their first physician visit.</li>
            <li><strong>Find an RRM-trained physician.</strong> The <a href="https://iirrm.org" rel="noopener">IIRRM referral network</a> connects you with credentialed providers. <a href="https://naturalwomanhood.org/find-a-doctor/" rel="noopener">Natural Womanhood's physician directory</a> is another resource. If you use a specific charting method, ask your instructor for provider recommendations within that method's network.<sup><a href="#ref-22" id="cite-22">22</a></sup></li>
            <li><strong>Prepare for your first appointment.</strong> Bring your charted cycles, complete medical history, prior lab and imaging results, and a list of questions. If you have a partner, have them attend. RRM evaluates both partners because male factor contributes to infertility in up to 40% of couples.<sup><a href="#ref-27" id="cite-27c">27</a></sup></li>
            <li><strong>Educate yourself.</strong> Browse free courses at <a href="/courses/">RRM Academy</a> to understand the approach, the conditions it treats, and what to expect from treatment. Knowledge helps you advocate for your own care.</li>
          </ol>

          <h3>For Healthcare Professionals</h3>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Start with online education.</strong> <a href="/courses/">RRM Academy courses</a> cover endometriosis, hormonal evaluation, surgical technique, and the fundamentals of cycle-based care.</li>
            <li><strong>Explore IIRRM credentialing.</strong> The <a href="https://iirrm.org" rel="noopener">International Institute for Restorative Reproductive Medicine</a> offers professional credentialing and hosts international conferences with CME credit.</li>
            <li><strong>Consider the FACTS medical elective.</strong> <a href="https://www.factsaboutfertility.org" rel="noopener">FACTS</a> provides a structured rotation for medical students and residents that introduces FABMs and RRM into clinical training.<sup><a href="#ref-21" id="cite-21b">21</a></sup></li>
            <li><strong>Pursue fellowship training.</strong> The Pope Paul VI Institute offers the most intensive training in NaProTechnology, covering advanced surgical techniques, hormonal protocols, and the full scope of restorative care.<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9b">9</a></sup></li>
          </ul>

          <h3>For Researchers</h3>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Browse the RRM Research Library.</strong> The <a href="https://library.rrmacademy.org">RRM Research Library</a> indexes over 3,000 publications relevant to restorative reproductive medicine, fertility awareness-based methods, and related clinical science.</li>
            <li><strong>Submit research.</strong> The <em>Journal of Restorative Reproductive Medicine</em> publishes peer-reviewed research in the field.</li>
            <li><strong>Attend conferences.</strong> IIRRM and IRRMA host annual conferences that bring together clinicians and researchers. These are the primary venues for presenting new findings and building collaborative networks.</li>
          </ul>

          <!-- Section 15: FAQ -->
          <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
          <div class="faq-accordion">
            <details>
              <summary>What is restorative reproductive medicine?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Restorative reproductive medicine (RRM) is a medical approach that diagnoses and treats the root causes of reproductive health conditions. Rather than masking symptoms with suppressive medications or bypassing natural function, RRM uses standard diagnostic tools and targeted treatments to restore the body's own reproductive physiology. RRM physicians are board-certified OBGYNs, reproductive endocrinologists, and family physicians with additional training in cycle-based evaluation.<sup><a href="#ref-1" id="cite-1d">1</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>Is RRM the same as NaProTechnology?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Not exactly. NaProTechnology is one specific approach within the broader field of restorative reproductive medicine. NaPro uses the Creighton Model FertilityCare System for charting and was developed at the Pope Paul VI Institute by Dr. Thomas Hilgers. RRM is the umbrella term that includes NaPro as well as other cycle-based, cause-directed medical approaches such as FEMM Medical Management and NeoFertility protocols.<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9c">9</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>How long does RRM treatment typically take?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Treatment timelines vary by diagnosis. Most couples begin with 1 to 3 cycles of charting to establish a baseline, followed by diagnostic testing and treatment planning. Some hormonal conditions respond within a few cycles of targeted support. Surgical cases (such as endometriosis excision) require recovery time before attempting conception. Overall, couples should expect an active treatment window of 3 to 18 months depending on complexity.<sup><a href="#ref-3" id="cite-3e">3</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>Does RRM work for male infertility?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Yes. RRM evaluates both partners. A male factor is solely responsible in about 20% of infertile couples and contributory in another 30 to 40%. Evaluation includes semen analysis, hormonal assessment, and investigation of anatomical issues such as varicocele. Treatment may include hormonal support, surgical correction, lifestyle modification, or referral to a urologist with reproductive expertise. Addressing both sides of the equation improves outcomes.<sup><a href="#ref-27" id="cite-27d">27</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>Can I try RRM if IVF has already failed?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Yes. Published research by Boyle et al. documented healthy singleton pregnancies from RRM treatment in couples who had previously undergone multiple failed IVF cycles. One case report describes a successful pregnancy after 16 years of infertility and eight unsuccessful IVF embryo transfers. RRM often uncovers treatable conditions that were never diagnosed during the IVF process.<sup><a href="#ref-17" id="cite-17d">17</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-10" id="cite-10c">10</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>Does insurance cover restorative reproductive medicine?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Many RRM treatments are covered by standard health insurance because they involve conventional diagnostics and treatments for diagnosed conditions. Bloodwork, imaging, medications, and surgery for endometriosis, PCOS, or hormonal disorders use standard medical billing codes. Arkansas became the first state to mandate coverage for restorative reproductive medicine in 2025. The federal RESTORE Act (H.R. 3589) has been introduced to expand access further. Coverage varies by plan and state.<sup><a href="#ref-15" id="cite-15b">15</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-20" id="cite-20b">20</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>Do I have to be Catholic or religious to use RRM?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>No. RRM is a medical discipline based on reproductive physiology, not religious doctrine. NaProTechnology was developed at a Catholic institution, but its protocols rely on the same science as any medical specialty. Patients of all faiths and no faith seek RRM because they want thorough diagnosis and cause-based treatment. No religious commitment is required.<sup><a href="#ref-1" id="cite-1e">1</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>What is the success rate of RRM?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Published studies report live birth rates of 26 to 41% (crude) for RRM treatment with timed intercourse, and adjusted cumulative rates of 50 to 62% depending on follow-up duration. Boyle et al. (2025) reported a 41% live birth rate in a 187-couple cohort.<sup><a href="#ref-24" id="cite-24">24</a></sup> Results depend on diagnosis, age, and individual factors. RRM also delivers outcomes beyond pregnancy: pain relief, hormonal balance, and answers about why a condition exists.<sup><a href="#ref-3" id="cite-3f">3</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-4" id="cite-4e">4</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>How is RRM different from seeing a regular OB-GYN?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Most OB-GYNs manage symptoms. Irregular periods get suppressive medications. Pelvic pain gets empiric treatment. Infertility gets a referral to IVF. An RRM physician starts with the cycle chart as a diagnostic tool, orders timed hormone panels based on cycle phase, investigates the root cause, and builds a targeted treatment plan. The tools are the same. The approach is different. RRM asks "why" before deciding "what."<sup><a href="#ref-7" id="cite-7d">7</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>Where can I find an RRM-trained doctor?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>The <a href="https://iirrm.org" rel="noopener">IIRRM provider directory</a> is the primary referral network for RRM-trained physicians. <a href="https://naturalwomanhood.org/find-a-doctor/" rel="noopener">Natural Womanhood</a> maintains a searchable directory. Each charting method has its own instructor network: <a href="https://www.fertilitycare.org" rel="noopener">FertilityCare Centers of America</a> for Creighton Model, the <a href="https://www.marquettemethod.com/instructors/" rel="noopener">Marquette Method Professionals Association</a> for Marquette, and <a href="https://femmhealth.org/teacher-directory/" rel="noopener">FEMM Health</a> for FEMM. Some RRM physicians offer telehealth consultations for patients without local access.<sup><a href="#ref-22" id="cite-22b">22</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>How much does RRM cost compared to IVF?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>RRM is typically far less expensive than IVF. One study found that IVF costs are on average 20 times greater than medication-based fertility treatments. A single IVF cycle costs $15,000 to $30,000, and most couples need two to three cycles, bringing average total costs to $40,000 to $60,000 or more. Many RRM treatments are billable under standard insurance codes for diagnosed conditions because RRM treats specific medical conditions rather than bypassing them.<sup><a href="#ref-15" id="cite-15c">15</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>What fertility charting methods are used in RRM?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>RRM physicians work with several validated fertility awareness-based methods (FABMs). The most commonly used include the Creighton Model FertilityCare System, the Marquette Method, FEMM (Fertility Education and Medical Management), the Billings Ovulation Method, and SymptoThermal methods. Each method tracks different biomarkers. The choice depends on the patient's needs and the physician's training. All provide cycle-based data that supports diagnosis.<sup><a href="#ref-5" id="cite-5f">5</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>Can RRM help with endometriosis?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Yes. RRM approaches endometriosis through thorough diagnostic evaluation (often including surgical assessment), excision surgery to remove endometriotic tissue, and targeted medical management to support healing and prevent recurrence. Excision is the gold standard for surgical treatment. RRM excision surgeons report repeat-surgery rates of just 2.5% over ten years, compared to up to 40% after ablation.<sup><a href="#ref-11" id="cite-11f">11</a></sup> RRM also addresses the pain, inflammation, and hormonal disruption that endometriosis causes.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>Is RRM safe?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>RRM uses standard medical and surgical interventions that carry the same safety profile as any conventional treatment. Bloodwork, imaging, and hormonal support carry minimal risk. Surgical interventions like laparoscopic excision carry the standard risks of any minimally invasive surgery. RRM does not involve the high-dose ovarian stimulation or egg retrieval procedures associated with IVF, which carry their own set of complications. RRM treats the underlying condition, which often improves the patient's overall health.<sup><a href="#ref-19" id="cite-19b">19</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>Can teenagers benefit from RRM?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Yes. Painful periods, irregular cycles, and heavy bleeding in teenagers deserve investigation, not suppression. The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recognizes the menstrual cycle as a vital sign in adolescents. RRM evaluation can identify conditions like endometriosis, PCOS, or hormonal imbalances early, when intervention is most effective. Learning a charting method also gives young women a tool for lifelong health monitoring.<sup><a href="#ref-14" id="cite-14b">14</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>Does my partner need to be involved?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>If you are seeking help with infertility, yes. Male factor contributes to infertility in a significant percentage of couples, and evaluation of only one partner misses half the picture. Your partner will typically need a semen analysis and may need hormonal testing. For non-fertility conditions (endometriosis, PCOS, pelvic pain), partner involvement is not required but can be supportive.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>What should I bring to my first RRM appointment?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Bring your charted cycles (at minimum 1 to 3 months of data), complete medical history, any prior lab or imaging results, a list of medications, and a list of questions. If you have prior surgical records or pathology reports, bring those as well. If you have a partner and are addressing fertility concerns, have them attend. The more data you provide, the more your physician can assess during the first visit.</p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>What is the difference between RRM and fertility treatment?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Conventional fertility treatment often focuses on achieving pregnancy by any means, frequently through assisted reproductive technologies like IVF and IUI. RRM focuses on diagnosing and treating the condition that prevents pregnancy. When the underlying disease is resolved, conception can occur through normal intercourse. RRM also treats conditions unrelated to fertility. The two approaches address different questions: "How do we achieve pregnancy?" versus "Why isn't it happening, and what can we fix?"<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6d">6</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>Can RRM help with conditions other than infertility?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Yes. RRM treats endometriosis, PCOS, pelvic pain, irregular or painful periods, PMS, PMDD, hormonal imbalances, thyroid disorders, ovulatory dysfunction, perimenopause, and other reproductive health conditions. RRM is a whole-body, couple-centered approach that includes functional nutrition, comprehensive metabolic bloodwork, mental health support, and lifestyle optimization alongside hormonal and surgical interventions. Many patients seek RRM without any fertility goals. They want their symptoms investigated and their conditions treated rather than managed indefinitely with suppressive medications.<sup><a href="#ref-1" id="cite-1f">1</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>

            <details>
              <summary>How do I become an RRM-trained provider?</summary>
              <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Start with online education through <a href="/courses/">RRM Academy</a>. For formal credentialing, the <a href="https://iirrm.org" rel="noopener">IIRRM</a> offers international certification and hosts conferences with CME credit. The Pope Paul VI Institute provides fellowship training in NaProTechnology. <a href="https://www.factsaboutfertility.org" rel="noopener">FACTS</a> offers a medical elective for students and residents. Cycle-based evaluation can be integrated into any OBGYN, family medicine, or endocrinology practice.<sup><a href="#ref-21" id="cite-21c">21</a></sup></p>
              </div>
            </details>
          </div>

